{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6d3a10bb-dcc9-4ddc-9078-6dcda005b216","content":"The directory is empty, so I'll create the workflow file and explain the nuget.org configuration steps.","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_JeYLL0lCH0tvscpkR52bB8","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /tmp/sv-bf08bae34db749eba2b67f247268b80f/.github/workflows","description":"Create workflows directory","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Create workflows directory"}],"interactionId":"9702254b-272d-4083-ab47-be7cfd573b37","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. I'll set up the project structure and the GitHub Actions workflow for trusted publishing. Let me create:\n\n1. The directory structure\n2. A GitHub Actions workflow for publishing via OIDC trusted publishing\n\nFor NuGet trusted publishing with OIDC, the key pieces are:\n1. A GitHub Actions workflow that requests an OIDC token with the `id-token: write` permission\n2. Using `dotnet nuget push` with `--source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json` and the `--api-key` set to the OIDC token (actually, NuGet's trusted publishing works differently)\n\n\n3. On nuget.org, I need to configure a trusted publisher linking to the specific GitHub repository and workflow, then the workflow requests an OIDC token and passes it to `dotnet nuget push`, which validates it against nuget.org's configuration. the token against the trusted publisher configuration. For the workflow, I need `permissions: id-token: write` to get the OIDC token, then use `dotnet nuget push` with the NuGet.org source and pass the token as the API key. Let me think through the exact current approach—it looks like recent versions of the dotnet CLI have built-in support for this, where the authentication happens automatically via the `ACTIONS_ID_TOKEN_REQUEST_URL` environment variable when pushing to NuGet.org. REQUEST_TOKEN` environment variables that GitHub Actions provides when you have `id-token: write` permission.\n\nWait, I need to be more precise. Let me think about what NuGet.org actually supports.\n\nAs of 2024-2025, NuGet.org supports trusted publishing. Here's how it works:\n\n**On nuget.org:**\n- Go to your account → Trusted Publishers\n- Add a new trusted publisher specifying:\n  - Repository owner (e.g., `myorg`)\n  - Repository name (e.g., `mylib`)  \n  - Workflow filename (e.g., `publish.yml`)\n  - Optionally, an environment name (e.g., `nuget.org`)\n\n**In the GitHub Actions workflow:**\n- Set `permissions: id-token: write`  \n- Pack the NuGet package\n- Push using the OIDC token\n\nFor the actual push command, the .NET SDK has native OIDC support in recent versions, so `dotnet nuget push` will automatically use the token when available. If I need more control, I can manually request the OIDC token and pass it as the API key. The approach mirrors PyPI's trusted publishing model—I register the trusted publisher on NuGet.org first, then the workflow authenticates using the OIDC token without needing to store secrets. The automatic OIDC authentication happens when the `id-token: write` permission is set and the GitHub Actions environment variables are available—the `dotnet nuget push` command in recent SDK versions will handle the token exchange transparently. I'm setting up the workflow with the necessary permissions, the dotnet setup step, and then the pack and push commands that leverage this OIDC flow.","outputTokens":1779,"requestId":"0413:322A6C:9AEC47:B517C1:69F3FB07"},"id":"643e822e-acf2-442d-ab82-a54d392badb8","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:00:22.396Z","parentId":"c424f792-b145-4834-a4ef-25e32bdf2e69"}
