{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1acdd46b-f586-4142-b947-2c475f12ebab","content":"Here's the workflow I created at `.github/workflows/publish.yml`. It uses OIDC (`id-token: write`) so no API key secret is needed.\n\n**You also need to configure nuget.org:**\n\n1. Go to [nuget.org → Manage Packages → Trusted Publishers](https://www.nuget.org/account/TrustedPublishers)\n2. Add a new trusted publisher with:\n   - **Repository owner:** `myorg`\n   - **Repository name:** `mylib`\n   - **Workflow filename:** `publish.yml`\n   - **Environment:** `nuget.org` (matches the workflow)\n\n**And on GitHub:**\n\n3. Create a repository environment named `nuget.org` at `Settings → Environments` (optional, but recommended for approval gates on publishes).\n\n**To publish**, push a version tag:\n```\ngit tag v1.0.0 && git push origin v1.0.0\n```\n\nThe `dotnet nuget push` command automatically uses the OIDC token from the GitHub Actions environment when `id-token: write` is granted and a matching trusted publisher is registered on nuget.org — no `--api-key` needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9702254b-272d-4083-ab47-be7cfd573b37","outputTokens":277,"requestId":"0413:322A6C:9B568B:B59604:69F3FB2C"},"id":"c56af601-689c-4baf-8d69-2c77151ff9d6","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:00:35.512Z","parentId":"70f32b1d-32a4-4649-a667-e57d8c27b144"}
